Kxf2 was also possibly but with Nxe4+ the queen is released. This move seems a good defense although the rook becomes trapped.

I wanted to keep the knight trapped and remove the protection of the f7 tile. This also releases the bishop.

Black could do 11. ... Nxc2 12. ... Na1 but doing that black loses its positional strength. And with 11. Qxf2 Ne4 black puts the f7 tile vulnerable.
Since white was so eager to defend c2 and consequently the rook, I brought the queen into game expecting a defensive maneuver of the c2 tile.
I think that was a strong play, trying to bring the knight into game, but probably c3 was better forcing black to move the knight.
